<!-- ════════ ARTICLE ════════ -->
<article>

<p class="lead">The gap between "I built a demo agent in an afternoon" and "we have a production agent serving real users" is enormous. The demo works 70% of the time and feels magical. The production system needs to work 99% of the time, at scale, under adversarial conditions, and fail gracefully when it doesn't. This post distills a comprehensive design framework into its core ideas.</p>

<p>Traditional ML has a well-worn lifecycle: define the problem, collect data, train a model, evaluate, deploy, monitor. LLM agents break this mold in subtle but important ways. You don't train the model (usually). You don't collect labeled datasets (often). Instead, you're doing architecture design, prompt engineering, tool integration, and guardrail construction. The work has shifted, but the need for rigor hasn't.</p>

<p>The framework presented here covers the full lifecycle in seven steps, from requirements to monitoring, with each step adapted for the specific challenges that agentic systems introduce.</p>

