<!-- ════════ STEP 1 ════════ -->
<h2><span class="step-num">01</span> Start With the Right Question</h2>

<p>In traditional ML, you separate "what's the business problem?" from "what model do we build?" For LLM agents, these are the same question. Choosing between a single LLM call, an agentic loop, or a multi-agent system is itself a core architectural decision that shapes everything downstream.</p>

<div class="callout tip">
  <div class="callout-title">The Golden Rule</div>
  <p>Start simple. Single LLM call first. Escalate to an agentic loop only when you can prove it's needed. Go multi-agent only when a single agent demonstrably can't handle the task. Complexity is always a cost.</p>
</div>

<p>The key tensions to navigate early: <strong>speed vs. quality</strong> (more reasoning steps yield better outputs but compound latency), <strong>autonomy vs. control</strong> (full autonomy for low-risk, human-in-the-loop for high-risk), and <strong>specialization vs. generality</strong> (specialized agents excel narrowly but multiply system complexity).</p>

<div class="divider"></div>

<!-- ════════ STEP 2 ════════ -->
<h2><span class="step-num">02</span> Design the Architecture</h2>

<p>This is the step that simply doesn't exist in traditional ML. For agents, architecture design (topology, reasoning patterns, tool schemas, inter-agent protocols) is as important as model selection. Maybe more.</p>

