<p class="diagram-caption">Three canonical patterns. Each trades simplicity for capability.</p>

<h3>Choosing a Reasoning Pattern</h3>
<p>The reasoning pattern determines how your agent thinks. <strong>ReAct</strong> interleaves thinking and acting in a loop: observe, reason, act, repeat. It's your default for tool-use tasks. <strong>Plan-then-Execute</strong> generates a full plan upfront, then executes step by step, yielding better reasoning quality but less adaptivity. <strong>Reflexion</strong> adds verbal self-critique after each attempt, letting the agent improve across trials without any weight updates. For long-horizon tasks with uncertainty, <strong>Plan-then-Execute with Re-planning</strong> combines planning quality with the ability to adapt when things go sideways.</p>

<div class="flow-tags">
  <span class="flow-tag" style="background:#e8f5f3;color:#2a8f82;">Simple tool-use → ReAct</span>
  <span class="flow-arrow">·</span>
  <span class="flow-tag" style="background:#eaf1f7;color:#3b6fa0;">Multi-step → Plan-Execute</span>
  <span class="flow-arrow">·</span>
  <span class="flow-tag" style="background:#f3eef8;color:#6b4c8a;">Iterative → Reflexion</span>
  <span class="flow-arrow">·</span>
  <span class="flow-tag" style="background:#fdf3e8;color:#d4843e;">Uncertain → Re-planning</span>
</div>

<h3>Don't Forget the Human</h3>
<p>Architecture decisions shape the user's experience. Research shows that users build mental models of what agents can and cannot do, and misaligned mental models lead to over-reliance or under-trust. The practical implications: expose the agent's plan and uncertainty (progressive disclosure works well), always let users override or cancel, and communicate confidence calibration. An agent that cannot be stopped is an agent that cannot be trusted.</p>

<div class="divider"></div>

<!-- ════════ STEP 3 ════════ -->
<h2><span class="step-num">03</span> Build the Knowledge and Tool Layer</h2>

<p>In traditional ML, "data prep" means building training datasets. For LLM agents, it means building knowledge infrastructure: RAG pipelines, vector stores, tool schemas, memory systems, and feedback loops. This is where most of the unglamorous but critical engineering happens.</p>

<p>Each tool needs a complete contract: name, description, typed parameters, return type, error types, timeout, and fallback behavior. Apply the principle of least privilege. Test that serialized results preserve the information your agent actually needs. On the prompt side, respect the instruction hierarchy (system > user > context) to guard against injection, version-control your prompts alongside code, and treat every prompt change as a deployment.</p>

<div class="divider"></div>

<!-- ════════ STEP 4 ════════ -->
<h2><span class="step-num">04</span> Develop the Agent</h2>

<p>In traditional ML, development means training. For LLM agents, you typically select a foundation model and then build around it. The real work is agent construction: memory architecture, persona design, MAS orchestration.</p>

<p>Model adaptation spans a spectrum from in-context learning (lowest barrier, context-window limited) through SFT and RL (PPO, DPO, GRPO, DAPO) to full distillation. Memory architecture needs careful thought: context window management (sliding window vs. summarization), external memory (vector DB, key-value), episodic memory for self-reflection, and shared memory design for multi-agent setups.</p>

<h3>Anthropomorphism as a Design Lever</h3>
<p>LLM agents inevitably exhibit anthropomorphic characteristics. Rather than treating this purely as a risk, it can be treated as a controllable design dimension. There are four categories of cues designers can tune: <strong>perceptive</strong> (avatar, interface style), <strong>linguistic</strong> (word choice, formality, humor), <strong>behavioral</strong> (turn-taking, proactivity, error acknowledgment), and <strong>cognitive</strong> (reasoning style, memory references). The key principle: every anthropomorphic feature should be <em>function-oriented</em>, serving a specific user goal rather than just making the agent feel human for its own sake.</p>

<div class="divider"></div>

<!-- ════════ STEP 5 ════════ -->
<h2><span class="step-num">05</span> Evaluate Rigorously</h2>

<p>Agent evaluation is harder than model evaluation. You're dealing with multi-step trajectories where many paths are valid, behavior is path-dependent and stochastic, MAS can exhibit emergent dynamics, and key properties are often latent. A single metric will mislead you.</p>

