<!-- ════════ STEP 6 ════════ -->
<h2><span class="step-num">06</span> Safety, Guardrails, and Deployment</h2>

<p>For agents that act autonomously, guardrail design is as important as the agent itself. The threat model covers prompt injection (direct and indirect), data leakage (PII, credentials), excessive agency (unauthorized actions), and system prompt leakage.</p>

<p>Guardrails operate at three layers: <strong>input</strong> (validate, reject adversarial prompts, detect injection), <strong>system prompt</strong> (instruction hierarchy, constitutional rules, persona boundaries), and <strong>output</strong> (filter PII, toxicity, hallucination, unauthorized actions; trigger retry or fallback). For multi-agent systems, guardrails must also cover inter-agent messages, and tool scoping via least privilege limits the blast radius of any single failure.</p>

<h3>Cost Engineering Matters</h3>
<p>MAS cost adds up fast: sum all input and output tokens across every agent call, including inter-agent communication. In practice, this is often 3 to 5 times the user-facing token cost. Smart routing (cheap model for easy queries, expensive for hard), semantic caching, prompt compression, and per-query budget enforcement are not optimizations; they're requirements for production viability.</p>

<div class="divider"></div>

<!-- ════════ STEP 7 ════════ -->
<h2><span class="step-num">07</span> Observe and Monitor</h2>

<p>For agentic systems, observability is a distinct discipline. You need distributed tracing (every LLM call, tool call, and inter-agent message as spans), prompt versioning (correlate prompt changes with metric shifts), trajectory replay (store and replay failed trajectories, the LLM equivalent of a stack trace), and real-time cost dashboards.</p>

